Time-resolved fluorescence (TRF) was used to gain insight into the GQD excited-state dynamics and the doping effect on the electronic band structure at λEx = 375 nm, and the emission was measured at λEm = 420 nm. Fig. 10
                      shows the relationship of TRF of GQDs before and after doping. In the case of O-GQDs, PL decay consists of two exponentials (τ1, τ2), while the PL decay of Cl-GQDs has a mono-exponential lifetime. The short relaxation lifetime τ1 is related to the electronic transitions of the carbon core, which is dramatically reduced from 690 ps to 5.3, 5, and 4 ps upon doping and becomes shorter with increasing dopant concentration in the order of Cl-GQD1> Cl-GQD2>Cl-GQD3. The long relaxation lifetime τ2 for O-GQDs is related to surface emissions (defects and substituents) (see Table 6

                     ) [94,99–101].
